Here's my function:

``` javascript
const ray_length = 1000
func screen_center_raycast (camera, caster):
    var from = camera.project_ray_origin(screen_center)
    var to = from + camera.project_ray_normal(screen_center) * ray_length

    var space_state = caster.get_world().get_direct_space_state()
    var result = space_state.intersect_ray( from, to, [ caster ] )

    return result
```

This function basically cast a ray from the center of the screen (like a common fps) 

and here is the call

``` javascript
func _fixed_process(delta):     
    if( right_click):
        right_click = false
        var result = global.screen_center_raycast(camera, self)
        if( result.has("collider") && result.has("shape") &&  result.has("normal")):
            print("right click " , result.collider , " " , result.shape , " " , result.normal)
            result.collider.right_click( result.shape, result.normal)
```

self is a rigidbody node and camera is a children camera node.

The problem is: the result of this function always return the "self" node which shouldn't since I gave "self" as an exclude for the raycast.

This bug is present in the latest sources but not in the 1.1 official release.
